<subSubSection id="44FFB0EAFFA5FFB9158BFD0EB7EBFC56" pageId="14" pageNumber="239" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0C5AE361FFA5FFB9158BFD0EB7EBFC56" blockId="14.[151,1437,151,898]" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis id="3E913F73FFA5FFB9158BFD0EB703FD7D" bold="true" box="[199,308,655,681]" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species was described from an unknown number of specimens (
<typeStatus id="D35E5DC3FFA5FFB9110AFD0EB295FD7D" box="[1094,1186,655,681]" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">syntype</typeStatus>
(s)) with the following data: “South 
<collectingCountry id="74F2A3F1FFA5FFB91466FD32B75FFD19" box="[298,360,691,717]" name="India" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">India</collectingCountry>
: Chikkaballapura (T.V. Campbell)“. The extant type was examined by 
<bibRefCitation id="68749E90FFA5FFB911C9FD32B3ABFD19" author="Zhang, Y. L. &amp; Webb, M. D." box="[1157,1436,690,717]" pageId="14" pageNumber="239" pagination="1 - 103" refId="ref11914" refString="Zhang, Y. L. &amp; Webb, M. D. (1996) A revised classification of the Asian and Pacific Selenocephalinae leafhoppers (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, Entomology Series, 65, 1 - 103." type="journal article" year="1996">Zhang &amp; Webb 1996: 25</bibRefCitation>
and designated as 
<typeStatus id="D35E5DC3FFA5FFB91425FD56B7E4FD25" box="[361,467,727,753]" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">lectotype</typeStatus>
. Among the species of 
<taxonomicName id="CBE598E2FFA5FFB91793FD56B560FD25" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1870" box="[735,855,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Drabescus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3E913F73FFA5FFB91793FD56B560FD25" box="[735,855,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">Drabescus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
without basal processes on the aedeagal shaft, this species can easily be recognised by the short aedeagal shaft with apical half expanded laterally and the style without subapical lobe. The female can be recognised by the sternite VII with a median V-shaped excavation on the posterior margin. This species occurs in southern states of peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="74F2A3F1FFA5FFB9167BFCC2B546FC89" box="[823,881,835,861]" name="India" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">India</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="CE212D83FFA5FFB91633FCC2B200FC89" box="[895,1079,835,861]" country="India" name="Andhra Pradesh" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">Andhra Pradesh</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="CE212D83FFA5FFB9110EFCC2B28FFC89" box="[1090,1208,835,861]" country="India" name="Karnataka" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">Karnataka</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="CE212D83FFA5FFB9118EFCC2B37FFC8A" box="[1218,1352,835,862]" country="India" name="Tamil Nadu" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">Tamil Nadu</collectingRegion>
) and in northeast 
<collectingCountry id="74F2A3F1FFA5FFB91449FCE6B708FC55" box="[261,319,871,897]" name="India" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">India</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="CE212D83FFA5FFB91401FCE6B7E7FC56" box="[333,464,871,898]" country="India" name="Meghalaya" pageId="14" pageNumber="239">Meghalaya</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
